Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit Donggala West in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Ring of Fire, an area of great seismic activity, and is frequently subject to earthquakes.
Following, we summarize some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of the past few years:
2004: A major earthquake in western Aceh Province, North Sumatra, on 26 December 2004 triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries and claimed the lives of 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast. More than half of the victims were in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes struck the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of deaths were reported on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake devastated southern Java, the most populous island in Indonesia, and triggered a tsunami that affected the southern coast, with nearly 700 fatalities.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
